                <h1>
                    2. Hello, World!
                </h1>
                <details>
                    <summary class="sum1">
                    2.1 Programs
                    </summary>
                <figure>
                    <img src="" width="40%">
                    <figcaption>
                    </figcaption>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    <b>Program</b> is a command which tells the computer what to do.
                    <b>Programming</b> is an activity of writing and testing such
                    programs.</br>
                </p>
                <p>
                Computers are dumb, in the sense that they require instructions
                to complete a certain task that a human can do with common
                sense.</br> &#10;

                The language in which instructions are  given is <b>programming 
                language.</b> C++ would be our programming language.
                </p>
                </details>
                <details>
                    <summary class="sum1">
                    2.2 The classic first program
                    </summary>
                <figure>
                    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Provincia_de_Buenos_Aires_-_Del_Viso_-_Ruper_saludando.jpg/360px-Provincia_de_Buenos_Aires_-_Del_Viso_-_Ruper_saludando.jpg" width="20%">
                    <figcaption>
                        Hello, world!
                    </figcaption>
                </figure>
                <h2>
                    Classic Hello World Program
                </h2>
                <PRE>
                //This program outpts "Hello World" to the monitor
                #include &lt; iostream &gt;
                int main() {
                    cout &lt;&lt;"Hello, World!\n";
                    return 0;
                }
                </PRE>
                <p>
                Let's understand the meaning of each line
                </p>
                <ol class="nested">
                    <li>
                        // This is a comment. It is ignored by the compiler.
                        Written to make code more readable.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        #include is a directive, instructs compiler to include
                        facilities from iostream
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        The main is the function, from where the computer
                        starts executing the code
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        cout refers to standard output stream, it is an
                        abbreviaton of "character output". character put in
                        cout using &lt;&lt; will appear on screen. </br></br>
                    </li>
                </ol>

                <p>
                Every C++ program should have a main function to tell from
                where to start executing the program. A function has four
                parts:
                </p>
                <ol class="nested">
                    <li>
                        <i> return type</i> specifies type of result that
                        particular function would return to the callee. 
                        int here.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <i>name</i>, here main
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <i>Parameter list</i> list of arguments the function
                        takes.empty in the above example
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <i>function body</i> enclosed in curly braces,which
                        lists the actions
                    </li>

                </ol>
                </details>
                <details>
                    <summary class="sum1">
                    2.3 Compilation
                    </summary>
                    <figure>
                        <img
                        src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Xxx_Scanner_and_parser_example_for_C.gif/800px-Xxx_Scanner_and_parser_example_for_C.gif"
                        width="30%">
                        <figcaption>
                            A parse tree for some C code.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                    C++ is a compiled language which means that the code 
                    has to be translated to machine level instructions.
                    Translation is done by a compiler
                    </p>
                    <p>
                    Source code is the code you write, for C++ the 
                    suffix is .cpp. The machine code or object code, 
                    is .o (Unix) or .obj(Windows) </br></br> 
                    Compiler checks for grammatically errors and/or syntax.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details>
                    <summary class="sum1">
                    2.4 Linking
                    </summary>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b1/Linker.svg/440px-Linker.svg.png"
                        width="24%">
                        <figcaption>
                            A linker.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        Several parts of code must be compiled and the
                        resulting code file must be linked together to form
                        an executable.Linker links such parts together 
                        to form an executable.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Object code and executables are not portable among 
                        systems i.e. Object code for windows will not run 
                        on Unix machines.</br></br>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <b>compile tim1e errors</b> errors found by compilers </br>
                        <b>link time errors</b> errors found by linkers</br>
                        <b> run time/logical errors</b> found when program is run
                        </br>
                    </p>

                </details>
                <details>
                    <summary class="sum1">
                    2.5 Programming environments
                    </summary>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e6/Anjuta-2.0.0-2.png/600px-Anjuta-2.0.0-2.png"
                        width="40%">
                        <figcaption>
                            The Anjuta IDE.
                        </figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                    To program we either use a command line or IDE.
                    To write and run a program, we require a certain
                    programming language, compiler, linker and an editor.</br>
                    </p>
                    <ul class="nested">
                        <li>
                            When using command line, you need to compile 
                            and link code by writing commands.
                        </li>
                        <li>   
                            IDE (Interactive development Environment) 
                            has a simple click button, which performs
                            the compile,link,run commands for you.</br>
                            IDE also has features like color coding 
                            to help distinguish between comments, 
                            keywords and other parts of program.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>
                    <b>Debugging</b> is used to find errors in program and remove them.
                    </p>
                </details>

            </div>
        </div>

